      "is_answer_order_important": false,
      "stimulus_html": "",
      "stem_html": "<p><i>Allenes</i> are compounds with adjacent carbon–carbon double bonds. Many allenes are chiral, even though they don’t contain chirality centers. Mycomycin, for example, a naturally occurring antibiotic isolated from the bacterium <i>Nocardia acidophilus,</i> is chiral and has [<i>α</i>]<sub>D</sub> = −130. Explain why mycomycin is chiral.</p>\n<img class=\"scaled-down\" src=\"https://exercises.openstax.org/rails/active_storage/blobs/proxy/eyJfcmFpbHMiOnsibWVzc2FnZSI6IkJBaHBBcE1SIiwiZXhwIjpudWxsLCJwdXIiOiJibG9iX2lkIn19--46c112519c543b6f36c09d0a4380ec34e5ec573c/OChem_05_EC_029.jpg\" alt=\"The condensed structural formula of mycomycin.\">",
